IMPORTANT — READ THIS ENTIRE AGREEMENT BEFORE ACCESSING, READING, CLONING,
OPERATING, BENCHMARKING, OR INTERACTING WITH THE PLANIT ROUTER SERVICE OR ANY
PORTION OF ITS SOURCE CODE OR INFRASTRUCTURE CONFIGURATION.

This License Agreement ("Agreement") is a legally binding contract between You
and Aakshat Hariharan ("Author") governing Your access to and use of the PlanIt
Router Service — the intelligent traffic management and request orchestration
layer that sits at the heart of the PlanIt platform's infrastructure.

The Router Service is not a commodity reverse proxy. It embodies proprietary
algorithms for adaptive backend selection, health-aware load distribution,
maintenance-safe traffic management, mesh-authenticated inter-service
communication, and white-label-aware routing that represent significant
engineering investment and constitute trade secrets of the Author. This
software is not available for use, adaptation, or deployment outside of
the Author's own infrastructure under any circumstances without a
separately executed written license.

================================================================================
SECTION 1 — DEFINITIONS
================================================================================

1.1   "Router Service" or "Software" means the PlanIt HTTP routing and
      orchestration layer in its entirety, including without limitation:

      (a)  All source code implementing the intelligent backend selection
           algorithm, including the scoring function, health-check polling
           loop, alive-state tracking, weighted cycling logic, boost mode
           configuration, and adaptive scaling heuristics;

      (b)  The maintenance intercept middleware and the _maintenanceExempt()
           exemption logic, including all hardcoded path exceptions and the
           rationale embedded in comments;

      (c)  The CORS management system, including the dynamic whitelist of
           allowed origins, the white-label domain registration mechanism,
           the Access-Control header injection logic, and the preflight
           handling;

      (d)  The mesh authentication protocol, including the SERVICE_NAME
           constant, the meshAuth() middleware factory, the shared secret
           scheme, and all inter-service communication endpoints under /mesh/;

      (e)  The response caching layer, including the cache key computation,
           TTL configuration, cache invalidation logic, and the list of
           cacheable route patterns;

      (f)  The rate limiting configuration, including per-path rate limit
           rules, the routerRateLimit middleware, and any IP-based throttling;

      (g)  The health check aggregation endpoint, its backend liveness testing
           logic, and the structured health response format;

      (h)  The deploy hook configuration, the backend fleet membership list,
           the backend URL registry (Maverick, Goose, Iceman, Slider, Viper),
           and all associated operational configuration;

      (i)  The WebSocket and Socket.IO proxying configuration and sticky-session
           routing logic;

      (j)  All configuration files, environment variable schemas, and
           deployment manifests associated with the Router Service;

      (k)  All documentation, comments, and architectural annotations embedded
           in or accompanying the Router Service.

1.2   "Author" means Aakshat Hariharan, the sole architect, developer, and
      intellectual property owner of the Router Service, its Routing
      Intelligence, and all proprietary systems embodied therein.

1.3   "You" or "Licensee" means any individual, engineer, DevOps professional,
      infrastructure architect, organization, company, or other legal entity
      that in any way reads, accesses, downloads, clones, deploys, operates,
      benchmarks, or otherwise interacts with the Router Service or any portion
      of its source code or configuration.

1.4   "Routing Intelligence" means the proprietary collection of algorithms,
      heuristics, scoring models, and decision logic that determine how the
      Router Service selects backend instances, manages health state, adapts to
      load conditions, and optimizes request distribution — including the
      specific threshold values, weight calculations, polling intervals, and
      adaptive scaling formulas — all of which constitute trade secrets of
      the Author.

1.5   "Hosted Infrastructure" means the production deployment of the PlanIt
      Router Service operated by the Author at planit-router.onrender.com,
      serving as the public entry point to the PlanIt platform.

1.6   "Backend Fleet" means the collection of PlanIt backend application
      server instances managed and orchestrated by the Router Service.

1.7   "Mesh Protocol" means the authenticated inter-service communication
      protocol implemented between the Router Service and the Backend Fleet,
      including HMAC-based mutual authentication, the /mesh/* endpoint
      namespace, and the meshAuth() verification middleware.

1.8   "Derivative Work" means any software, service, infrastructure component,
      or other work that: (a) is derived from or copies any portion of the
      Router Service; (b) reimplements the Routing Intelligence; (c) uses the
      Router Service's source code as a reference implementation; or (d) is
      functionally equivalent to or substantially similar to the Router Service
      in design or operation.

1.9   "Deploy" means to execute, run, host, containerize, or otherwise operate
      the Router Service or any portion thereof on any computing infrastructure.

1.10  "Commercial Use" means operating the Router Service or any Derivative
      Work in connection with any revenue-generating commercial activity.

